responses.TaxoWhatImp: This allow to have a better understanding of the rule and it help to not reproduce the non-compliant code

responses.UserFeedback: I think a rule need to specify for which langage it is usefull. For exemple Kotlin as a completely different syntax than Java for ex. And a bad practice for one langage could maybe be a good one for another.

responses.TaxoWhatImp: precise trigger conditions are important. They must describe the portion of code that triggers the rule to help understand what code needs to be revised. But also, specific criteria (metrics and or keywords) should be listed/highlighted as well, as those can help identify a false positive. Happens a lot with regular expressions based rules.
responses.TaxoWhyImp:
The why needs to express the associated RISKS, either direct because the code may be a source of bug, or indirect/mid/long term because may be a source of errors in the future.
The why should justify the effort needed to fix/address the problem.
responses.TaxoFixImp: The fix is needed to illustrate how to avoid the problem explained in the why. It is likely the coder introduced a bad pattern/error due to lack of expertise; as such, it would be wrong to assume he/she will know how to fix it.
responses.TaxoOther:
there should other attributes:
1. a confidence level regarding the what, ranging from: this is no doubt an ill pattern, down to, this looks bad, you need to confirm this is normal; this could be linked to how to ignore the issue: it could be automatic for low confidence (warning), to harder for more certain one
2. a risk domain for the why: is this a security issue, a performance issue, a maintainability issue... . This helps a team focusing on certain attributes that are important for the project, instead of improving quality on all axes, which is good, but expensive

responses.TaxoWhatImp: many different things may be discussed/considered on a single piece of code, so it's important to clearly identify what is the precise topic when a notification pops
responses.TaxoWhyImp: applying the rule is a thing, understanding why this rule exists and what's the sense/value behind it is really important to me. it's also a better way to remember it.
responses.TaxoFixImp: it's really saving time when fix is clearly suggested, it avoids also browsing all the web to read maaaaaaany discussions on the topic... ideal thing is to just click a button to 'autofix' the issue, when available
responses.TaxoOther: detailing with examples the potential exceptions where the rule does not apply is also very interesting
responses.UserFeedback: while links may give a lot of useful information, it's mandatory get the the right info to be efficient directly at first step when a warning/error from the linter pops => no click needed to understand what happens and how to fix it.

responses.TaxoWhatImp: Identifying what triggers the rule might not be obvious.
responses.TaxoWhyImp:
This helps to understand rules and avoid a feeling of arbitrariness and dogma (avoids the "we do this like this and that's it").
It also teaches the underlying topic and can be an opportunity for developer to grow.
responses.TaxoFixImp: Solutions might not be obvious, especially in cases where something is deprecated or suboptimal and better methods are not known by the developer.
responses.TaxoOther:
Linter can help teach good practices and idiomatic patterns.

Like a compiler with good error messages, a linter can be a teaching tool help to cover the extra miles to further improve on code that is valid but suboptimal.

Custom project specific or team specific rules can also help onboard new developers and help refactoring (i.e. stop using this deprecated thing and do this instead).

responses.TaxoWhatImp: First I very much doubt that complex rules can be precisely described by a what. It is wishful thinking that the effort would be put into defining what should be and should not be captured by the rule exactly. In practice, a programmer stumbles upon an issue that looks like a linter issue and only read the specs when believes that the linter is wrong or failed to capture. At that point, the "what" is very important.
responses.TaxoWhyImp: Linters are one of the best ways to learn how to properly program in a new language (eg. Resharper for C#)—explaining why is a valuable lesson to learn. If well defined, the "why" includes and supersedes the what. If an expert in the language the why can help to confirm whether one wants to activate/deactivate the rule.
responses.TaxoFixImp: So you can have the linter stop complaining.
responses.TaxoOther:
Yes: limitations. Limitations can be considered part of the "what", but I did not see this anywhere.
Linters are often heuristics and very often only handle subsets of the what. What they compute is often not decidable, and limitations should be defined.
responses.UserFeedback:

responses.TaxoWhatImp: I believe understanding the What purpose is a requirement for properly understanding the Why purpose (which I also believe is important). The two of them combined help understand what may be wrong in a piece of code concerned by the rule, which helps a developer (1) understand why the might want to use this rule or not and (2) improve their development skills by learning to detect potential pitfalls, code smells, etc.
responses.TaxoWhyImp: It goes hand in hand with the What purpose (see my other comment).
responses.TaxoFixImp: I believe the Fix purpose is important, although not as much as the What and Why purpose. It is important because it helps developers fix a mistake or improve the code, but not as important, as a linting rule may already be helpful by detecting a situation requiring the developer's attention and explaining what is or may be wrong with it, even though it may not suggest how to fix it (the developer may still know how to fix it, or search for a fix).
responses.TaxoOther: Yes: describing linter/rule settings related to what is being documented. For example, a linter documentation may let users configure a rule to only apply in a subset of situations, or alter the style of the code transformation that may be automatically performed by the linter to fix non-compliant code.
responses.UserFeedback: The documentation of the rule about short casts of booleans in PHP was really blunt and unclear. Others were sometimes a little unsatisfactory, e.g., because they lacked a proper explanation of what the rule targeted, why the rule described a bad behaviour, or what would be a better alternative. In particular, I disliked documentation in which the information was only present in example code or in a linked document, but not as text, as it requires more effort from the developer to investigate what the rule is about/why does it matter/why does it suggest this fix rather than another one.

responses.TaxoFixImp:
Fixes such as the ENV.fetch() example are good because they give the user an easy way to improve their code. However, sometimes the fix suggestions may cause problems. In my particular experience, with a python library, the linter was suggesting that I should remove an unused import. It was something like:

import foo
import foo.utils as u

For some reason, I had to explicitly import the foo.utils library (even though I did not use access it directly as "u.function()", I still had to call foo.utils in my code). However, I suppose this is a particular issue with the library or environment I was using.

responses.TaxoWhatImp:
A linter documentation is important to be present for several purposes, such as:

To explain what a linter is and how it can help improve the quality, readability, maintainability, security, and performance of the code.
To provide instructions on how to install, configure, use, and extend the linter tool of choice.
To list and describe the rules, options, and features that the linter tool supports and enforces.
To provide examples of code that passes or fails the linter checks and how to fix the errors or warnings.
To offer troubleshooting tips and FAQs for common issues or questions that users may encounter when using the linter tool.
responses.TaxoWhyImp:
A comparison with other linter tools and their advantages and disadvantages.
A history of the development and evolution of the linter tool and its community.
A contribution guide for users who want to help improve the linter tool or its documentation.
responses.TaxoFixImp: The Fix purpose is important to be present in the documentation because it helps users to correct the errors or warnings that the linter tool detects and reports
responses.TaxoOther:
I think these are some of the main purposes that a linter documentation should have, but there may be others depending on the specific linter tool and its target audience. For instance, some linter documentation may also include:

- A comparison with other linter tools and their advantages and disadvantages.
- A history of the development and evolution of the linter tool and its community.
- A contribution guide for users who want to help improve the linter tool or its documentation.
responses.UserFeedback:
I appreciate that you liked the clarity, completeness, and organization of the documentation. I agree that these are important aspects of a good documentation, as they help users to understand and use the linter tool effectively.
I understand that you disliked the lack of examples and screenshots in some parts of the documentation. I think that these are useful features that can enhance the documentation, as they can provide visual and practical guidance for users. I suggest that the documentation could include more examples and screenshots to illustrate the usage and output of the linter tool, especially for complex or advanced features.

responses.TaxoWhatImp: The "What" category in the documentation is important because it provides clarity, context, and efficiency in troubleshooting issues related to linter rules, thus enhancing the overall code quality.

responses.UserFeedback: Overall, I was impressed with the quality of the linter documentation that I saw. The documentation was clear, concise, and informative. It explained the purpose of each rule, the potential issues and pitfalls of violating the rule, and how to avoid violating the rule.

responses.TaxoWhatImp: It is essential to help the developper know when the rule is expected to be applied (and when the linter won't be able to detect a violation of the good practice behind the rule). It also serves as an example for better understanding the "why" part of the rule.
responses.TaxoWhyImp:
It is better to understand the reason behind a rule than to follow it blindly. 
It might educate the user about good practices and design that can extend behind the scope of the rule.
This information is needed to create the  rules subset that fits your development context, if the linter allows such configuration.
responses.TaxoFixImp:
When the fix is rather straightforward, it is useful to know  it  as it  can help understanding the rule and if the fix can be applied automatically it allows to preview the changes.
However, in other cases it can lead beginners to apply a cascade of bad decisions made to satisfy the linter at the expense of the design consistency.
responses.UserFeedback:
I appreciated rules that specified correctly the Why and What parts, preferably in text.
Some of them went beyond my expectations in this regard. I appreciated the most the ones in which the "What Why Fix" were present in short form then detailed later and with further info given in links.  
Additional info I want to find in a linter documentation (which I should have put in the appropriate field in the beginning of the survey) : a categorization of rules, using tags.
